-- South African Stocks Decline, Led Lower by BHP, Anglo Platinum, Old Mutual
-- B y   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n
-- 2010-10-26T15:35:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-26/south-african-stocks-fall-anglo-american-arcelormittal-old-mutual-move.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  lost 128.86, or 0.4 percent, to 30,133.78 at the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up almost 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark
stock index, fell 1.99 rand, or 0.6 percent, to 321.91 rand.
Copper retreated as much as 1 percent to $8,435 a metric ton on
the London Metal Exchange.  Shares in larger rival  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ) dropped
1.90 rand, or 0.8 percent, to 242 rand.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s largest producer
of the metal, slipped to the lowest in three weeks, retreating
16.10 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 686.90 rand. The company is
facing a protest by a local community in South Africa’s Limpopo
province over access to land, the South African Press
Association reported.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd.  (ACL SJ), a unit of the
world’s biggest steelmaker, declined 2.30 rand, or 2.8 percent,
to 81 rand, the lowest since Oct. 11. The company said fourth-
quarter profit will drop because of lower prices and a seasonal
slowdown in domestic sales.  Esorfranki Ltd.  (ESR SJ), a provider of engineering
services to builders, slipped the most in three weeks, dropping
3 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 2.05 rand. Earnings per share
excluding one-time items declined 90 percent in the first half
through August, the company said in a stock-exchange filing.  Old Mutual Plc  (OML SJ), Africa’s biggest insurer, slumped
for a sixth day, the longest streak of losses since March 2009,
falling 27 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 14.42 rand. The
recommendation on the company was reduced to “neutral” from
“buy” at Bank of America Merrill Lynch.  Vunani Ltd.  (VUN SJ): The stock-broking company fell 1
cent, or 13 percent, to 7 cents, the lowest since Oct. 22. The
company said it is in talks with Kagiso Trust Investments about
the possible acquisition of Kagiso Securities.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Garth Theunissen  in Johannesburg 
